<subSubSection id="45AA9C0720F6E0685786ABED8AF7EAF6" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="A074775F28100C8AAFE4E50C745DFCC9" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BC75832A695F3ECC5D1277D71526BD44" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
The species is dedicated to the deceased Brazilian writer Jorge Amado, who was born in Bahia state in 1912 and died in 2001. Amado is one of the most acclaimed contemporary Brazilian novelists, whose 32 novels have sold millions of copies. Among his best-known works are 
<normalizedToken id="0FE45FD85F56B5AF6D5FD24307D77029" originalValue="â€œCapitÃ£es">&quot;Capitaes</normalizedToken>
de Areia&quot;, &quot;Gabriela, Cravo e Canela&quot;, and &quot;Tieta do Agreste&quot;. In 2012, Brazil celebrated the centenary of his birth.
</paragraph>
